• Sampling and Computation: In the loop(), repeatedly measure waveforms. For example, EmonLib’s emon1.calcVI (wavelengths, timeout) can capture a set number of AC cycles, then compute all quantities. Under the hood, the library multiplies each instantaneous voltage and current sample and accumulates them. Real (active) power is calculated as the average of these instantaneous products over the sample set. Separately, RMS values are computed by squaring each sample, averaging, and taking the square root. The library reports results such as real power (P), apparent power 

